            "id": "berserker",
            "name": "Berserker",
            "fullName": "Path of the Berserker",
            "parentClassId": "barbarian",
            "parentClass": "Barbarian",
            "sourceBookOrCommonReference": "Player's Handbook",
            "description": "Path of the Berserker is built around unrestrained fury, frenzy, and the brutal fantasy of a warrior who burns through exhaustion and fear to keep attacking. It gives the barbarian a sharper identity than the base class alone, turning ordinary training into a specific tradition, philosophy, curse, talent, or calling. In play, this subclass emphasizes direct melee pressure with simple choices, high damage, intimidation, and risk-reward endurance. The character’s decisions should therefore feel different from another barbarian with the same core features, because this path changes how they approach danger, allies, preparation, and victory. For story use, it easily supports a raider, pit fighter, berserk champion, bodyguard, or traumatized survivor whose rage becomes momentum. DMs can attach mentors, rivals, orders, taboos, ceremonies, reputations, and personal costs to that concept. For players, it rewards committing to the fantasy instead of treating the subclass as a passive bonus: describe how the power looks, what habits it creates, and what enemies notice when it appears. In an NPC generator, this subclass should influence goals, equipment, social role, downtime work, and battlefield behavior. Allies should know what this person is trusted to do, while enemies should understand why meeting them is dangerous. This entry is associated with Player's Handbook in common 5e reference use, but this summary is original and avoids reproducing official rules text. The rage should feel like a doorway into this path’s myth, not just a damage switch.",
