            "sourceBookOrCommonReference": "Player's Handbook",
            "description": "College of Lore is built around scholarship, stories, secrets, satire, and the bard as a collector of everything worth knowing. It gives the bard a sharper identity than the base class alone, turning ordinary training into a specific tradition, philosophy, curse, talent, or calling. In play, this subclass emphasizes skills, magical versatility, cutting remarks, and the ability to borrow solutions from many traditions. The character’s decisions should therefore feel different from another bard with the same core features, because this path changes how they approach danger, allies, preparation, and victory. For story use, it easily supports an archivist, gossip-master, wandering professor, oral historian, or comedian whose jokes expose tyrants. DMs can attach mentors, rivals, orders, taboos, ceremonies, reputations, and personal costs to that concept. For players, it rewards committing to the fantasy instead of treating the subclass as a passive bonus: describe how the power looks, what habits it creates, and what enemies notice when it appears. In an NPC generator, this subclass should influence goals, equipment, social role, downtime work, and battlefield behavior. Allies should know what this person is trusted to do, while enemies should understand why meeting them is dangerous. This entry is associated with Player's Handbook in common 5e reference use, but this summary is original and avoids reproducing official rules text. The performance style, chosen art, and social mask should all reflect the college. For Belavadös-style use, connect it to local biomes, accents, factions, and cultural pressures so the same subclass can still produce many distinct characters.",
