            "description": "Wild Magic Sorcerous Origin is built around unpredictable innate magic, reality hiccups, and power that misfires beautifully or dangerously. It gives the sorcerer a sharper identity than the base class alone, turning ordinary training into a specific tradition, philosophy, curse, talent, or calling. In play, this subclass emphasizes chaotic surges, luck manipulation, and comic or catastrophic battlefield twists. The character’s decisions should therefore feel different from another sorcerer with the same core features, because this path changes how they approach danger, allies, preparation, and victory. For story use, it easily supports a spellstorm survivor, fey-touched child, unstable prodigy, or living crack in magical law. DMs can attach mentors, rivals, orders, taboos, ceremonies, reputations, and personal costs to that concept. For players, it rewards committing to the fantasy instead of treating the subclass as a passive bonus: describe how the power looks, what habits it creates, and what enemies notice when it appears. In an NPC generator, this subclass should influence goals, equipment, social role, downtime work, and battlefield behavior. Allies should know what this person is trusted to do, while enemies should understand why meeting them is dangerous. This entry is associated with Player's Handbook in common 5e reference use, but this summary is original and avoids reproducing official rules text. The origin should feel involuntary and intimate, as if magic has opinions about the sorcerer’s body and emotions. For Belavadös-style use, connect it to local biomes, accents, factions, and cultural pressures so the same subclass can still produce many distinct characters.",
