            "parentClass": "Warlock",
            "sourceBookOrCommonReference": "Player's Handbook",
            "description": "Fiend Otherworldly Patron is built around bargains with devils, demons, hellish powers, and patrons who reward destruction. It gives the warlock a sharper identity than the base class alone, turning ordinary training into a specific tradition, philosophy, curse, talent, or calling. In play, this subclass emphasizes temporary vitality from defeated foes, firepower, luck manipulation, and infernal resilience. The character’s decisions should therefore feel different from another warlock with the same core features, because this path changes how they approach danger, allies, preparation, and victory. For story use, it easily supports a desperate survivor, ambitious occultist, redeemed sinner, or warlock trying to out-lawyer hell. DMs can attach mentors, rivals, orders, taboos, ceremonies, reputations, and personal costs to that concept. For players, it rewards committing to the fantasy instead of treating the subclass as a passive bonus: describe how the power looks, what habits it creates, and what enemies notice when it appears. In an NPC generator, this subclass should influence goals, equipment, social role, downtime work, and battlefield behavior. Allies should know what this person is trusted to do, while enemies should understand why meeting them is dangerous. This entry is associated with Player's Handbook in common 5e reference use, but this summary is original and avoids reproducing official rules text. The patron should remain present through symbols, dreams, debts, loopholes, gifts, and quiet pressure. For Belavadös-style use, connect it to local biomes, accents, factions, and cultural pressures so the same subclass can still produce many distinct characters.",
