            "description": "Genie Otherworldly Patron is built around elemental nobles, wishcraft, portable sanctums, and patronage from dao, djinni, efreeti, or marids. It gives the warlock a sharper identity than the base class alone, turning ordinary training into a specific tradition, philosophy, curse, talent, or calling. In play, this subclass emphasizes elemental damage, vessel utility, flight or resistance themes, and flexible spell flavor. The character’s decisions should therefore feel different from another warlock with the same core features, because this path changes how they approach danger, allies, preparation, and victory. For story use, it easily supports a lamp-bound traveler, treasure broker, desert envoy, or servant who may become a partner. DMs can attach mentors, rivals, orders, taboos, ceremonies, reputations, and personal costs to that concept. For players, it rewards committing to the fantasy instead of treating the subclass as a passive bonus: describe how the power looks, what habits it creates, and what enemies notice when it appears. In an NPC generator, this subclass should influence goals, equipment, social role, downtime work, and battlefield behavior. Allies should know what this person is trusted to do, while enemies should understand why meeting them is dangerous. This entry is associated with Tasha's Cauldron of Everything in common 5e reference use, but this summary is original and avoids reproducing official rules text. The patron should remain present through symbols, dreams, debts, loopholes, gifts, and quiet pressure. For Belavadös-style use, connect it to local biomes, accents, factions, and cultural pressures so the same subclass can still produce many distinct characters.",
