            "sourceBookOrCommonReference": "Player's Handbook",
            "description": "School of Abjuration is built around wards, counterspells, protection, and magic as a shield against disaster. It gives the wizard a sharper identity than the base class alone, turning ordinary training into a specific tradition, philosophy, curse, talent, or calling. In play, this subclass emphasizes defensive barriers, spell resistance, and ally protection through arcane preparation. The character’s decisions should therefore feel different from another wizard with the same core features, because this path changes how they approach danger, allies, preparation, and victory. For story use, it easily supports a ward architect, exorcist scholar, academy safety officer, or paranoid genius who survives first. DMs can attach mentors, rivals, orders, taboos, ceremonies, reputations, and personal costs to that concept. For players, it rewards committing to the fantasy instead of treating the subclass as a passive bonus: describe how the power looks, what habits it creates, and what enemies notice when it appears. In an NPC generator, this subclass should influence goals, equipment, social role, downtime work, and battlefield behavior. Allies should know what this person is trusted to do, while enemies should understand why meeting them is dangerous. This entry is associated with Player's Handbook in common 5e reference use, but this summary is original and avoids reproducing official rules text. The tradition should reveal how the wizard organizes reality: as defense, force, symbols, time, minds, death, or carefully edited perception. For Belavadös-style use, connect it to local biomes, accents, factions, and cultural pressures so the same subclass can still produce many distinct characters.",
